As I come to this morning, I got another fantastic idea that I need help with.

It's a game concept, which I would make, but I haven't the slightest where to begin in game development. I have a story, an art style and more that suddenly came to me. I'm not saying it's an easy task making a video game, but I know what I am after.

I've been told that VG development is difficult before but it hasn't stopped me, what has stopped me, is my lack of knowledge. I'm looking into a book that should help guide me through Unity (not the preferred game engine for this, but acceptable nonetheless), but I still feel there is a disconnect.

For any of you who honestly know me on the forum, this may sound like a lie to grab pitiful attention, but it's not- I was diagnosed with mild Autism very young and I struggled to pick up English. I spoke in what my parents jokingly called, "Klingon". I had my own language as a child with everything having a name and even being able to make commands in this made up language. (Point being) I struggled with English and I recently picked up another language and I struggled the same as I did with English. Coding, which is essential in game development, is just another language. I want to learn how to do programming and eventually become good enough to move onto another aspect of game design, but I just can't right now. I need help as it's all too foreign and I feel I need a more guiding hand to help sort through the mess that is coding. So if anyone wants to help me bridge this gap, it would be greatly appreciated.

Or if you simply want to let me drive the story and design it yourself, I'd be good with that too  . I just feel this is a fantastic idea and I don't want my inabilities to lead to such a good idea being lost. I'll start writing things out on paper as time goes on so maybe I can save it before the idea leaves me or loses shine.

8 hours ago, ZooNamedGames said:

Apologies if this question is off the mark, but just to verify (and no criticism intended, I'm honestly curious)-- have you actually tried some coding, or is this an assumption based on your past difficulties with language acquisition?

I only ask because there's a very big difference between computer languages and human ones:  the computer languages make more sense.  They're completely logical, completely consistent, and completely unambiguous.

I only mention it because I've been in the software industry a long time, and dealt with a lot of computer-geek types.  I'd say that the software biz is actually a magnet for borderline-autistic types-- many such folks actually gravitate towards software as a career.  I know that a lot of folks on the autism spectrum can have language issues, but my impression is that in many cases, a big part of that is due to the need to read ambiguity, emotional context, etc. out of the communication, which is an especial challenge for autism.  Computers dispense with all of that, which can make things a lot simpler for such folks.

I'm not presuming to know anything about your own challenges, or trying to paint all autism-spectrum individuals with the same brush.  If you've already tried coding and have found language-related difficulty with it, then never mind all of the above.

I only bring it up on the off chance that maybe you haven't actually tried much coding yet and might just be assuming that it would be as hard for you as a human language-- which it might not be.

Changed Course

By: ZooNamedGames

Authors Note:

    This isn't mean to be an accurate depiction of events but rather a retake on a series of events as if one major event happened which could have changed them.

Introduction:

    It's October 5th, 1957. We all watched the television screen from our desks as news announced to us the launch of Sputnik, a Soviet space probe. 
    Our teacher, a leading scientist in his growing field of rockets, said to us, "This is the beginning of something big". 
    We were a group of five students from our small college in Huntsville, Alabama. We were the "nerds" to the majority of people, with our white dress shirts, pocket protectors, and dress pants. 
    What we didn't know, was that we would all branch out, and lead events which would create the greatest achievement of mankind. We were the the members of a small aerospace class which had been newly started at the time.
    We were few. There was Harold Jackson, a genius in mathematics. No problem stopped him, if he couldn't solve it, then he passed it to his closet friend, Malcolm Foster. 
    Malcolm was unique in every way, and looking back, he solved more critical problems of the space race than anyone I can think of. 
    Malcolm tended to think of problems as personal challenges and would see to dedicating all of his time to solving, no matter how trivial the matter was. 
    He would break problems down into the simplest form and setting the variables apart so he could see the issue at hand. Then he would draw out elaborate and extensive plans and diagrams to further illustrate the problem to himself.
    Malcolm's only weakness was machinery, he found them too unreliable and likely to fail. If there was ever a problem in that regard, we past it to Kevin Carter.
    Kevin was the only one of us to truly understand machinery. He began as a mechanic working on old cars with his fathers until he later moved onto a job repairing old television sets. 
    That's where his love of machinery hit him, he learned how delicate yet complex they could be. It all made sense to him. 
    Then there was Jack Davis, the wildcard of our class. He would not seem to belong with us, a bunch a nerds, but he brought something none of us could to the table, motivation. 
    If there was a problem we all gave up on, there was him to hype us up. He never let us give up early on anything, in fact he never quit on anything.
    Jack was also had a lot of "free spirit", which would land him in major trouble at times. However he never let his troubles inhibit his work, when he set out to succeed in something, he did. 
    Lastly, there was me, Christopher T. Fields. I was a hometown boy in Alabama. I had never left the county line much less town. I stayed in school, and worked hard at it, but I was no smarter than anyone else: 
    It seemed I had nothing to do past school, until I picked up a book by Jules Vern, From The Earth To The Moon. It opened up a whole new world to me, that I had never seen before. 
    I had read the Buck Rogers comics and such, but I never realized how close we were to making space a reality. It was then I wanted to learn.
    I brought what the others couldn't bring to the table, imagination. I could draw out the path we needed to take, what something should look like. Everyone else in our class seemed to not be able to draw something out if there wasn't anything to go on, but I could.
    However the greatest source of our success, and my lifetime hero, was our professor Mr. Gray. He was our leader and the reason behind our success.
    Mr. Gray understood us and the material extremely well. He could explain something to us in our own individual ways. He had been an  airforce engineer so he had experience with the real thing. 

    "Do you think the Reds are spying on us Mr. Gray"?, asked Malcolm,.
    "Not likely. A camera would be to heavy, especially with the proper communication equipment and battery", responded Mr. Gray.
    Jack was one to know the military advantage of a camera in space, so he knew to ask, "Do you think this could lead to a larger probe which could spy on us?".
     Mr. Gray frowned and looked down, but then he said "Very possibly", then he looked back to us, "but that's what your working on! Beating them to it".
    Jack smiled at that and then jumped from his seat and ran towards the front of the classroom where Mr. Gray was and asked, "In light of this, I would like to see us do more hands on work".
    "More hands on?", returned Mr. Gray.
    "Yeah, let's make rockets, real rockets".
    "You do realize that they're extremely dangerous... And difficult to make".
    "I do, I mean, we do. Moreover, I want to see my work".
    "You always want to see your work.... But I think we can do that. Let's start small and make basic working liquid fuel. Sound good to you?"
   "Heck yeah!", and with that we all shouted our approval.
